Our word for money itself was derived from pecus, ‘ cattle ¹, and even now in the censor's accounts all the sources of national revenue are termcd ‘ pastures ’‚ because rent of pasture—land was for a long time the only source of public income. Moreover fines were only specified in terms of payment of sheep and oxen3 nor must we omit the benevolent spirit of the law of early times, in that a judge imposing a fine was prohibited from specifying an ox before he had previously fined the offender a sheep. There were public games in honour of oxen‚ those eonducting them being called the Bubetii. King Servius stamped first the bronze coinage with the likencss of sheep and oxen. Indeed the Twelve Tables made pasturing animals by stealth at night on crops grown under the plough, or cutting it, a capital offence for an adult, and enacted that a person found guilty of it should be executed by hanging‚ in reparation to Ceres, a heavier punishment than in a conviction for homicide ; while a minor was to be flogged at the discretion of the praetor ora sentenced to pay the amount of the damage or twice that amount. In fact the system of class and office in the state itself was derived from no other source.
